			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">If using two CPLDs is cost effective that certainly shouldn't be ignored. I think to get both the homebrew base covered as well as the bit more shadey reproduction base you'd want to make a MMC3 compatible if not straight clone. Because if it is compatible with all existing MMC3 software that ensures a market will exist and you won't end up stuck with unsold units. 
<br />
<br />Particularly if the board can by like the RetroZone boards where the one board can be configured for various standards of the TxROM.
<br />
<br /><div class="quotetitle">bunnyboy wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">512KB PRG (Battle Kid 2), self flashable (not yet used), and 4x 8KB CHR RAM banks (Assimilate) are very cheap additions to UNROM.  Like the 8T-ROM using flash instead of battery backed WRAM removes much of the need for MMC1/MMC3.  The CHR banking makes background animations usually done with CHR ROM easy.  Still no IRQ but $5-10 cheaper per cart.</div>
<br />
<br />With the 32K CHR-RAM, is it just hooking up the upper bits to hold a 8KB CHR-RAM page I would guess? 
<br />
<br />Part of the reason to have a MMC3 for homebrew is definitely to have alot of CHR, which no homebrew yet has needed but certainly could happen. Alot of great games have such nice graphics thanks to tons of CHRROM.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

